    <section id="warnings">
      <h2>Warnings</h2>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Knowing Principles Is Not the Same as Applying Them">
        The most common failure mode in engaging with timeless wisdom is the mistaking of intellectual understanding for actual practice. You can read every great book on virtue, purpose, and deliberate practice without changing a single behavior. The principles described in this article are widely known and minimally practiced. The gap between knowing and doing is bridged only by the deliberate design of specific behavioral changes, accountability structures, and regular honest self-assessment. Reading is the beginning, not the end.</ContentBox>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Timeless Principles Still Require Contextual Application">
        The universality of these principles does not mean their application is uniform across all situations. How you pursue clarity of purpose when you are twenty-two is different from how you pursue it at forty-five. What deliberate practice looks like in surgery is different from what it looks like in creative writing. The principles are stable; their implementation is contextual and requires the practical wisdom (itself a timeless principle) to discern what they require in your specific circumstances at your specific stage of life.
      </ContentBox>
      <ContentBox type="warning" title="Warning: Ancient Wisdom Had Blind Spots Too">
        The convergence of ancient wisdom across cultures is impressive, but it would be intellectually dishonest to apply these principles uncritically without noting that many ancient traditions had significant blind spots — particularly regarding who was considered eligible for excellence and achievement. Aristotle's ethics excluded women and slaves; Confucian philosophy was often hierarchically conservative; Stoic cosmopolitanism was more theoretical than practical in its treatment of social inequality. The principles of character, practice, purpose, resilience, and relationship are genuinely universal — but their application should be informed by everything that subsequent centuries have learned about justice and the full scope of human dignity.
      </ContentBox>
    </section>

